Shoulder biomechanics (force couples)

Transverse plane force couple

  • Used in the treatment of end-stage
    • steoarthritis, severe pain, reduced range of motion, and loss of muscle strength

Osteoarthritis affects 1.8 million Australians Today, 14% of Australians are aged 65 years and older, projected to increase to 25% by 2050

Rotator Cuff Tears

  1. of people in their seventh decade, and over
  2. of people over the age of 80 will suffer a full- thickness rotator cuff tear. Results in:
  3. Pain
  4. Shoulder instability
  5. Shoulder dislocation
  6. Loss of shoulder movement
  7. Inability to perform activities of daily living

* Milgrow. et al JBJS (Am), 1995

• Used in the treatment of rotator cuff tear arthropathy (when the glenohumeral joint is unstable), but also trauma and tumour resection

  • RTSA comprises three-quarters of all shoulder arthroplasties performed in Australia (AOANJRR)
  • Rotator cuff tears and arthritis present in
    1. of cases (Schairer et al. 2015)
  • Complication rates have ranged between
    1. and 68% (up to 90% in smaller studies)
  • Dislocation accounts for 44% of complications (Edwards et al. 2009)

Schairer et al. (2015) National utilization of reverse total shoulder arthroplasty in the United States. J Shoulder Elbow Surg 24:91-97. Edwards TB et al. (2009). Subscapularis insufficiency and the risk of shoulder dislocation after reverse shoulder arthroplasty. J Shoulder Elbow Surg 18:892-896.

  • Muscle forces cannot be measured (non-invasively)
  • Patient-specific musculoskeletal models can estimate muscle forces using physiological cost functions and constraints
  • Models should be derived and validated using experimental data (e.g. cadaveric testing, instrumented implants etc.)

Summary

  • Increases in muscle moment arms after RTSA reduces muscle forces (greater range of motion, improved joint function)
  • This ultimately decreases joint compression, which may lead to dislocation (deltoid tension critical)
  • More superior joint shear that compression
    • ccurs after RTSA (subluxation risk)

What about implant loading?

Need to solve a mathematical problem: Input is bite force, outputs are muscle forces and TMJ force

Then, use calculated muscle forces to drive finite element model simulation of implant loading

Summary

  • Prosthesis tailored to patient
  • Reduced risk of intra-operative complication
  • Improved jaw function and diet
  • Rapidly fabricated (3D printing): print to order
  • Cost benefits

Courtesy: The Age

Overall summary

• Reverse shoulder arthroplasty, performed to restore shoulder function in cases of rotator cuff tears and

end-stage OA (i.e. rotator cuff tear arthropathy), improves joint stability but can present risk of superior subluxation

• Computational modelling and 3D printing facilitates personalised implant development for the jaw, with cost and practical benefits
